<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-852-660  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 852 660.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MIS Week  Oct 30 1989 v10 n43 p41(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>CAD hard copy turns to 3-D, makes use of 'sintering'.andO;(computer-aided design)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Coursey, David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>One of manufacturing's new technologies is a device that creates3-D prototypes from a computer-aided design (CAD) model.andP;  DTM Corpplans to market a process called 'selective laser sintering' (SLS)for creating models out of powdered material.andP;  The word'sintering' suggests any process causing particles to form a solidmass by means of externally applied energy.andP;  A program that slicesthe CAD model into cross sections is part of SLS systems.andP;  Theprototype is created by raster-scanning successive layers of poweruntil the entire object is created.andP;  Each layer is sintered tobond it to the underlying layer.andP;  A variety of materials can beused to make these prototypes: investment-casting waxes,polymer-coated ceramics, and metal powders.andP;  Other companies areusing different terminology, such as 'stereolithography', todefine similar products.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   DTM Corp. (product development).andO;Topic:     Computer-Aided DesignNew TechniqueThree-Dimensional GraphicsRaster ScanSolids ModelingPrototypeStereolithography.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Selective laser sintering system. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>